A shooting at Westroads Mall in Omaha left eight dead, including the gunman, Robert A. Hawkins.
Witnesses described chaos as gunfire rang out, with victims chosen randomly.
Hawkins, troubled and depressed, left a note expressing remorse before taking his own life.
President Bush, who had been in Omaha earlier, expressed sadness over the tragedy.
The community mourned the loss of innocent lives and offered support to those affected.
The incident highlighted the prevalence of gun violence in the United States, sparking discussions on mental health and gun control.
The mall remained closed as authorities investigated the motive behind the shooting spree.
